SIMPLE: intensive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intensive
<hw>In*ten"sive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>intensif</ets>. See <er>Intense</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Stretched; admitting of intension, or increase of
degree; that can be intensified.</def> <rj><au>Sir M.
Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by persistence; intent; unremitted;
assiduous; intense.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir H.
Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Serving to give force or
emphasis; <as>as, an <ex>intensive</ex> verb or
preposition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>Designating, or pertaining to,
any system of farming or horticulture, usually practiced on small pieces
of land, in which the soil is thoroughly worked and fertilized so as to
get as much return as possible; -- opposed to
<contr>extensive</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intensive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intensive
<hw>In*ten"sive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which intensifies or
emphasizes; an intensive verb or word.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intensively</ent>⟦br⟧
